owl:ObjectProperty.obo:IAO_0000116: Everything is part of itself. Any part of any part of a thing is itself part of that thing. Two distinct things cannot be part of each other.

Occurrents are not subject to change and so parthood between occurrents holds for all the times that the part exists. Many continuants are subject to change, so parthood between continuants will only hold at certain times, but this is difficult to specify in OWL. See https://code.google.com/p/obo-relations/wiki/ROAndTime

Parthood requires the part and the whole to have compatible classes: only an occurrent can be part of an occurrent; only a process can be part of a process; only a continuant can be part of a continuant; only an independent continuant can be part of an independent continuant; only an immaterial entity can be part of an immaterial entity; only a specifically dependent continuant can be part of a specifically dependent continuant; only a generically dependent continuant can be part of a generically dependent continuant. (This list is not exhaustive.)
A continuant cannot be part of an occurrent: use 'participates in'. An occurrent cannot be part of a continuant: use 'has participant'. A material entity cannot be part of an immaterial entity: use 'has location'. A specifically dependent continuant cannot be part of an independent continuant: use 'inheres in'. An independent continuant cannot be part of a specifically dependent continuant: use 'bearer of'.

Containment obtains in each case between material and immaterial continuants, for instance: lung contained_in thoracic cavity; bladder contained_in pelvic cavity. Hence containment is not a transitive relation. If c part_of c1 at t then we have also, by our definition and by the axioms of mereology applied to spatial regions, c located_in c1 at t. Thus, many examples of instance-level location relations for continuants are in fact cases of instance-level parthood. For material continuants location and parthood coincide. Containment is location not involving parthood, and arises only where some immaterial continuant is involved. To understand this relation, we first define overlap for continuants as follows: c1 overlap c2 at t =def for some c, c part_of c1 at t and c part_of c2 at t. owl:ObjectProperty.obo:IAO_0000116: Location as a relation between instances: The primitive instance-level relation c located_in r at t reflects the fact that each continuant is at any given time associated with exactly one spatial region, namely its exact location. Following we can use this relation to define a further instance-level location relation - not between a continuant and the region which it exactly occupies, but rather between one continuant and another. c is located in c1, in this sense, whenever the spatial region occupied by c is part_of the spatial region occupied by c1. Note that this relation comprehends both the relation of exact location between one continuant and another which obtains when r and r1 are identical (for example, when a portion of fluid exactly fills a cavity), as well as those sorts of inexact location relations which obtain, for example, between brain and head or between ovum and uterus

'In engineering terms, soil is referred to as regolith, or loose rock material that lies above the 'solid geology'. Soil is commonly referred to as "earth" or "dirt"; technically, the term "dirt" should be restricted to displaced soil.' https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Soil
" The upper limit of soil is the boundary between soil and air, shallow water, live plants, or plant materials that have not begun to decompose. Areas are not considered to have soil if the surface is permanently covered by water too deep (typically more than 2.5 meters) for the growth of rooted plants.
The lower boundary that separates soil from the nonsoil underneath is most difficult to define. Soil consists of horizons near the Earth's surface that, in contrast to the underlying parent material, have been altered by the interactions of climate, relief, and living organisms over time. Commonly, soil grades at its lower boundary to hard rock or to earthy materials virtually devoid of animals, roots, or other marks of biological activity. For purposes of classification, the lower boundary of soil is arbitrarily set at 200 cm." owl:Class.rdfs:comment: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ In the Udden-Wentworth scale (due to Krumbein), silt particles range between 0.0039 to 0.0625 mm, larger than clay but smaller than sand particles. ISO 14688 grades silts between 0.002 mm and 0.063 mm. In actuality, silt is chemically distinct from clay, and unlike clay, grains of silt are approximately the same size in all dimensions; furthermore, their size ranges overlap. Clays are formed from thin plate-shaped particles held together by electrostatic forces, so present a cohesion. According to the U.S. Department of Agriculture Soil Texture Classification system, the sand-silt distinction is made at the 0.05 mm particle size. The USDA system has been adopted by the Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO). In the Unified Soil Classification System (USCS) and the AASHTO Soil Classification system, the sand-silt distinction is made at the 0.075 mm particle size (i.e., material passing the #200 sieve). Silts and clays are distinguished mechanically by their plasticity.

owl:Class.obo:IAO_0000115: Ecozones delineate large areas of a planetary surface within which organisms have been evolving in relative isolation over long periods of time, separated from one another by geographic features, such as oceans, broad deserts, or high mountain ranges, that constitute barriers to migration.
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: ENVO contains this top-level class, but all instances will be in GAZ. The definition is preliminary and will be aligned to BFO. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ Ecozones correspond to the floristic kingdoms of botany or zoogeographic regions of zoology. Ecozones are characterized by the evolutionary history of the organisms they contain. They are distinct from biomes, also known as major habitat types, which are divisions of the Earth's surface based on life form, or the adaptation of plants and animals to climatic, soil, and other conditions. Biomes are characterized by similar climax vegetation. Each ecozone may include a number of different biomes. A tropical moist broadleaf forest in Central America, for example, may be similar to one in New Guinea in its vegetation type and structure, climate, soils, etc., but these forests are inhabited by plants and animals with very different evolutionary histories.

owl:Class.skos:definition: A surface layer of a water body which is part of an ocean or sea.

owl:Class.obo:IAO_0000115: A surface layer of an astronomical body which is primarily composed of solid material and is not covered by oceans or other bodies of water.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: land
owl:Class.skos:definition: A surface layer of an astronomical body which is primarily composed of solid material and is not covered by oceans or other bodies of water.

owl:Axiom.owl:annotatedTarget: A surface layer of an astronomical body which is primarily composed of solid material and is not covered by oceans or other bodies of water.

owl:Class.rdfs:label: ecosystem process
owl:Class.skos:definition: An environmental process either driven by or primarily impacting the parts or emergent properties of an ecosystem.

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: This is a convenience class for organisation and should not be used for annotation.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: environmental system process
owl:Class.skos:definition: A process in which includes the components of an environmental system as participants.

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: This class will be populated by inference and is primarily organisational.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: atmospheric process
owl:Class.skos:definition: A process which occurs within an atmosphere.

owl:Class.rdfs:label: anthropogenic environmental process
owl:Class.skos:definition: An environmental process which is driven by the action of humans.

owl:Class.obo:IAO_0000115: An action of exogenic processes (such as water flow or wind) which remove environmental material from one part of a planet's crust, transporting it to another location where it is deposited.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: planetary erosion
owl:Class.skos:definition: An action of exogenic processes (such as water flow or wind) which remove environmental material from one part of a planet's crust, transporting it to another location where it is deposited.

owl:Axiom.owl:annotatedTarget: An action of exogenic processes (such as water flow or wind) which remove environmental material from one part of a planet's crust, transporting it to another location where it is deposited.

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: This classes asserted subclasses will be moved away as it should be an inferred class.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: hydrological process
owl:Class.skos:definition: An environmental process which has water - in any of its states - as a participant.

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Experimental class for structural purposes not recommended for annotation. A material accumulation process ends a material transport process.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: material accumulation process
owl:Class.skos:definition: A process during which the mass of one or more materials, present within a given site, increases.

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Experimental class for structural purposes not recommended for annotation.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: material transport process
owl:Class.skos:definition: A process during which material is displaced from its original location and transported either to a new location or back to the original location.

owl:Class.obo:IAO_0000115: Sediment which has been transported through the marine water column, settling on the seafloor.
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Particles of marine sediment are primarily generated by 1) processes in terrestrial systems and transported to the marine realm by the action of rivers or aeolian processes (amongst other routes) , 2) marine organisms, 3) chemical processes in seawater, or 4) cosmogeneous input.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: marine sediment
owl:Class.skos:definition: Sediment which has been transported through the marine water column, settling on the seafloor.

owl:Axiom.owl:annotatedTarget: Sediment which has been transported through the marine water column, settling on the seafloor.

owl:Class.rdfs:label: sedimentation in a water body
owl:Class.skos:definition: A material accumulation process during which solid particles are pulled through a water body by gravitation or centrifugal force and which ends when they settle on a solid surface.

owl:Class.obo:IAO_0000116: A different material transformation process class (or similarly named class) pertaining to the conversion of a specific chemical into another belongs in CHEBI and or REX ontologies.
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Experimental class for structural purposes not recommended for annotation. A material transformation process only refers to ENVO:environmental material classes (e.g. bulk and typically impure substances), rather than transformations converting a specific chemical into another.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: material transformation process
owl:Class.skos:definition: A process during which a portion of some environmental material is converted into a different material or a collection of materials.

owl:Class.rdfs:label: porosity of soil
owl:Class.skos:definition: The porosity of some soil.

owl:Class.rdfs:label: composition of soil
owl:Class.skos:definition: The composition of some soil.

owl:Class.rdfs:label: structure of soil
owl:Class.skos:definition: The structure of some soil.

owl:Class.rdfs:label: wetness of soil
owl:Class.skos:definition: The wetness of some soil.

owl:Class.rdfs:label: composition of water
owl:Class.skos:definition: The composition of some water.

owl:Class.rdfs:label: anatomical entity environment
owl:Class.skos:definition: An environment which is determined by an anatomical entity.

owl:Class.rdfs:comment:
per the definition of 'contiguous' of "being in actual contact : touching along a boundary or at a point", these land masses share boundaries with other land masses that are part of the same continent, and thus are not surrounded by water like an island.
At some point, we need an 'adjacent to' relation if BFO doesn't provide it.
One question is whether this class encompasses fiat parts of islands.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: contiguous land mass

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: It cannot be a part of the island, for example, that is below water.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: contiguous island land mass
owl:Class.skos:definition: A subcontinental land mass that is part of an island and includes part of the land surface of the island.

owl:Class.rdfs:label: geographical region
owl:Class.skos:definition: A geographical entity that is demarcated at least in part by one or more closed fiat boundaries all of whose lines are part of the planetary surface.

owl:Class.obo:IAO_0000115: The production of new individuals that contain some portion of genetic material inherited from one or more parent organisms.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: reproduction
owl:Class.skos:definition: The production of new individuals that contain some portion of genetic material inherited from one or more parent organisms.

owl:Axiom.owl:annotatedTarget: The production of new individuals that contain some portion of genetic material inherited from one or more parent organisms.

owl:Class.obo:IAO_0000115: Any process specifically pertinent to the functioning of integrated living units: cells, tissues, organs, and organisms. A process is a collection of molecular events with a defined beginning and end.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: biological process
owl:Class.skos:definition: Any process specifically pertinent to the functioning of integrated living units: cells, tissues, organs, and organisms. A process is a collection of molecular events with a defined beginning and end.

owl:Axiom.owl:annotatedTarget: Any process specifically pertinent to the functioning of integrated living units: cells, tissues, organs, and organisms. A process is a collection of molecular events with a defined beginning and end.

owl:Class.obo:IAO_0000115: The increase in size or mass of an entire organism, a part of an organism or a cell.
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: See also the biological process term 'cell growth ; GO:0016049'.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: growth
owl:Class.skos:definition: The increase in size or mass of an entire organism, a part of an organism or a cell.

owl:Axiom.owl:annotatedTarget: The increase in size or mass of an entire organism, a part of an organism or a cell.

owl:Class.obo:IAO_0000115: A dependent entity that inheres in a bearer by virtue of how the bearer is related to other entities
owl:Class.rdfs:label: quality
owl:Class.skos:definition: A dependent entity that inheres in a bearer by virtue of how the bearer is related to other entities

owl:Axiom.owl:annotatedTarget: A dependent entity that inheres in a bearer by virtue of how the bearer is related to other entities

owl:Class.rdfs:label: composition
owl:Class.skos:definition: A single physical entity inhering in an bearer by virtue of the bearer's quantities or relative ratios of subparts.

owl:Class.rdfs:label: morphology
owl:Class.skos:definition: A quality of a single physical entity inhering in the bearer by virtue of the bearer's size or shape or structure.

owl:Class.rdfs:label: shape
owl:Class.skos:definition: A morphological quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's ratios of distances between its features (points, edges, surfaces and also holes etc).

owl:Class.rdfs:label: deviation (from normal)
owl:Class.skos:definition: A quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the whether the bearer differs from normal or average.

owl:Class.rdfs:label: size
owl:Class.skos:definition: A morphology quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's physical magnitude.

owl:Class.rdfs:label: mass
owl:Class.skos:definition: A physical quality that inheres in a bearer by virtue of the proportion of the bearer's amount of matter.

owl:Class.rdfs:label: position
owl:Class.skos:definition: A spatial quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's spatial location relative to other objects in the vicinity.

owl:Class.rdfs:label: structure
owl:Class.skos:definition: A morphology quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's relative position, shape, arrangements and connectivity of an organism's various parts; the pattern underlying its form.

owl:Class.rdfs:label: decreased size
owl:Class.skos:definition: A size quality which is relatively low.

owl:Class.rdfs:label: opacity
owl:Class.skos:definition: An optical quality which obtains by virtue of the ability of the bearer to absorb visible light.

owl:Class.rdfs:label: opaque
owl:Class.skos:definition: A optical quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's not being clear; not transmitting or reflecting light or radiant energy.

owl:Class.rdfs:label: permeability
owl:Class.skos:definition: A structural quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's disposition to being permeated or pervaded by a gas or liquid (as by osmosis or diffusion).

owl:Class.rdfs:label: porosity
owl:Class.skos:definition: A permeability quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's disposition to admit the passage of gas or liquid through pores or interstices.

owl:Class.rdfs:label: porous
owl:Class.skos:definition: A porosity quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's being capable of admitting the passage of gas or liquid through pores or interstices.

owl:Class.obo:IAO_0000115: A quality of a physical entity that exists through action of continuants at the physical level of organisation in relation to other entities.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: physical quality
owl:Class.skos:definition: A quality of a physical entity that exists through action of continuants at the physical level of organisation in relation to other entities.

owl:Axiom.owl:annotatedTarget: A quality of a physical entity that exists through action of continuants at the physical level of organisation in relation to other entities.

owl:Class.rdfs:label: elongated
owl:Class.skos:definition: A quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's length being notably higher than its width.

owl:Class.rdfs:label: strength
owl:Class.skos:definition: A quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's power or force.

owl:Class.obo:IAO_0000115: A quality which inheres in a continuant.
owl:Class.oboInOwl:hasExactSynonym: multiply inhering quality of a physical entity
quality of a single physical entity
owl:Class.rdfs:label: physical object quality
owl:Class.skos:definition: A quality which inheres in a continuant.

owl:Axiom.owl:annotatedTarget: A quality which inheres in a continuant.

owl:Class.obo:IAO_0000115: A physical quality that inheres in an bearer by virtue of how that bearer interacts with electromagnetic radiation.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: electromagnetic (em) radiation quality
owl:Class.skos:definition: A physical quality that inheres in an bearer by virtue of how that bearer interacts with electromagnetic radiation.

owl:Axiom.owl:annotatedTarget: A physical quality that inheres in an bearer by virtue of how that bearer interacts with electromagnetic radiation.

owl:Class.obo:IAO_0000115: An EM radiation quality in which the EM radiation is within the fiat range of the spectrum visible deemed to be light.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: optical quality
owl:Class.skos:definition: An EM radiation quality in which the EM radiation is within the fiat range of the spectrum visible deemed to be light.

owl:Axiom.owl:annotatedTarget: An EM radiation quality in which the EM radiation is within the fiat range of the spectrum visible deemed to be light.

owl:Class.rdfs:label: amorphous
owl:Class.skos:definition: A morphology quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's lack of distinct morphology.

owl:Class.rdfs:label: increased position
owl:Class.skos:definition: A position which is relatively high.

owl:Class.rdfs:label: decreased position
owl:Class.skos:definition: A positional which is relatively low.

owl:Class.rdfs:label: sloped
owl:Class.skos:definition: A shape quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's having an oblique or slanted direction.

owl:Class.rdfs:label: increased mass
owl:Class.skos:definition: A mass which is higher than normal or average.

owl:Class.rdfs:label: elevation
owl:Class.skos:definition: A positional quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's vertical distance of a point above or below a reference surface.

owl:Class.rdfs:label: increased elevation
owl:Class.skos:definition: An elevation which is relatively high.

owl:Class.rdfs:label: decreased elevation
owl:Class.skos:definition: An elevation which is relatively low.

owl:Class.obo:IAO_0000115: A quality that inheres in an bearer by virtue of how that bearer interacts with radiation.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: radiation quality
owl:Class.skos:definition: A quality that inheres in an bearer by virtue of how that bearer interacts with radiation.

owl:Axiom.owl:annotatedTarget: A quality that inheres in an bearer by virtue of how that bearer interacts with radiation.

owl:Class.rdfs:label: granular
owl:Class.skos:definition: A composition quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's containing granules.

owl:Class.rdfs:label: wetness
owl:Class.skos:definition: A quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of whether the bearer's being covered by a liquid.

owl:Class.rdfs:label: wet
owl:Class.skos:definition: A wetness quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's being covered by a liquid.

owl:Class.rdfs:label: laminar
owl:Class.skos:definition: A quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's processing the form of a thin plate sheet or layer.

owl:Class.rdfs:label: displaced
owl:Class.skos:definition: A positional quality inhering in a bearer by virtue the bearer's being changed in position.

owl:Class.rdfs:label: quality of a substance
owl:Class.skos:definition: A quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of its constitution.

owl:Class.rdfs:label: increased quality
owl:Class.skos:definition: A quality that has a value that is increased compared to normal or average.

owl:Class.rdfs:label: decreased quality
owl:Class.skos:definition: A quality that has a value that is decreased compared to normal or average.

owl:Class.rdfs:label: decreased object quality
owl:Class.skos:definition: A quality of an object that has a value that is decreased compared to normal or average.

owl:Class.rdfs:label: increased object quality
owl:Class.skos:definition: A quality of an object that has a value that is increased compared to normal or average.

owl:Class.rdfs:label: collection of organisms
collection of organisms
owl:Class.skos:definition: A material entity that consists of two or more organisms, viruses, or viroids.

owl:Class.rdfs:label: population of organisms
owl:Class.skos:definition: A collection of organisms, all of the same species, that live in the same place.

owl:Class.rdfs:label: single-species collection of organisms
owl:Class.skos:definition: A material entity that has as parts two or more organisms, viruses, or viroids of the same species and no members of any other species.

owl:Class.rdfs:label: multi-species collection of organisms
owl:Class.skos:definition: A collection of organisms that consists of two or more organisms from at least two species.

owl:Class.rdfs:label: anatomical structure
owl:Class.skos:definition: Material anatomical entity that is a single connected structure with inherent 3D shape generated by coordinated expression of the organism's own genome.

owl:Class.rdfs:label: morphological feature
owl:Class.skos:definition: A part of an organism or organ that is continuous with its surroundings and distinguished from its surroundings based on morphology.

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: the effective number of different species that are represented in a collection of individuals, it consists of two components: species richness and species evenness. From http://cerrado.linkeddata.es/ecology/ccon#SpeciesDiversity
owl:Class.rdfs:label: species diversity index
absence
owl:Class.skos:definition: Not existing in a specified place at a specified time.

owl:Class.rdfs:label: alien range
owl:Class.skos:definition: An area in which a species occurs even though it lies outside its native range.

owl:Class.rdfs:label: alien species
owl:Class.skos:definition: Species whose presence in a region is attributable to human actions that enable them to overcome biogeographical barriers.

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: after https://www.thefreedictionary.com/allocation
owl:Class.rdfs:label: allocation
owl:Class.skos:definition: To set apart or re-distribute for a special purpose

owl:Class.rdfs:label: animal diversity
owl:Class.skos:definition: Variety of animal species present in a location

owl:Class.rdfs:label: animal nutrient
owl:Class.skos:definition: chemical element required by animals to perform functions necessary for life

owl:Class.rdfs:label: anthropogenic disturbance
owl:Class.skos:definition: disturbance brought about by human activity

owl:Class.rdfs:label: area
owl:Class.skos:definition: A geographical region that can include land as well as water.

owl:Class.rdfs:label: behavioural change
owl:Class.skos:definition: Any change in the behaviour of a species

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: from https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Beta_diversity
owl:Class.rdfs:label: beta diversity
owl:Class.skos:definition: In ecology, beta diversity (Î²-diversity or true beta diversity) is the ratio between regional and local species diversity.

owl:Class.rdfs:label: beta diversity index
owl:Class.skos:definition: metric for estimating beta diversity

owl:Class.rdfs:label: change in environment
owl:Class.skos:definition: Any change in the environment, e.g. concerning temperature, soil nutrients or biodiversity

owl:Class.rdfs:label: change in individual
owl:Class.skos:definition: Any change in an individual organism, e.g. concerning its size or life cycle stage

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: definition from: http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/PCO_000000
owl:Class.rdfs:label: community
owl:Class.skos:definition: A community of at least two different species, living in a particular area. Must have at least two populations of different species as members.

owl:Class.rdfs:label: competitive strength
owl:Class.skos:definition: A species is strongly competitive, if its way of using shared resources usually leads to a reduction in survivorship, growth and/or reproduction of at least some of the competing individuals of the other species.

owl:Class.rdfs:label: compound property
owl:Class.skos:definition: Attribute resulting from a combination of several traits

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: from http://vivoweb.org/ontology/core#Continent
owl:Class.rdfs:label: continent
owl:Class.skos:definition: A large contiguous landmass that is at least partially surrounded by water, together with any islands on its continental shelf.

owl:Class.rdfs:label: disturbance
owl:Class.skos:definition: A disturbance is an event or process that disrupts ecosystem, community or population structure, and changes resources, substrate availability or the physical environment. Disturbances can have anthropogenic or non-anthropogenic causes.

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: From http://www.fao.org/aims/aos/cwr.owl#Diversity
owl:Class.rdfs:label: diversity
owl:Class.skos:definition: 1) The variety of plant and animal taxa, including genes, amino acids, flowers, species, or populations. 2) The variety of plant and animal communities, forest types, stand conditions, age classes, and landscape components.

owl:Class.rdfs:label: ecological impact
owl:Class.skos:definition: A measurable change to the properties of an ecosystem by a non-native species.

owl:Class.rdfs:label: ecological measure
owl:Class.skos:definition: metric for qualifying ecologically relevant characteristics, e.g. biodiversity or body length

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: from http://www.openness-project.eu/taxonomy/term/73
owl:Class.rdfs:label: ecosystem property
owl:Class.skos:definition: Attributes which characterize an ecosystem, such as its size, biodiversity, stability, degree of organization, as well as its functions and processes (i.e. the internal exchanges of materials, energy and information among different pools).

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: from http://www.projecthalo.com/aura#Ectoparasite
owl:Class.rdfs:label: ectoparasite
owl:Class.skos:definition: A parasite that lives on and feeds from the external surface of the host's body.

owl:Class.rdfs:label: enemy
owl:Class.skos:definition: An organism that is a predator, consumer, parasite, parasitoid or pathogen of another organism.

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: after Reiss, J., Bridle, J.R., Montoya, J.M. and Woodward, G. 2009. Emerging horizons in biodiversity and ecosystem functioning research. Trends Ecol. Evol., 24: 505-514, and McGill BJ, Enquist BJ, Weiher E, Westoby M (2006) Rebuilding community ecology from functional traits Trends Ecol Evol 21:178-185
owl:Class.rdfs:label: functional trait
owl:Class.skos:definition: A trait that strongly influences organismal performance, and that determines its effect on processes and its response to environmental factors

owl:Class.rdfs:label: generalist
owl:Class.skos:definition: A species that can survive and reproduce in a wide range of environmental conditions using a wide variety of resouces to do so.

owl:Class.rdfs:label: genetic change
owl:Class.skos:definition: Any change in the genome of a species

owl:Class.rdfs:label: genetic characteristic
owl:Class.skos:definition: Information about the genetic characteristics

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: from https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Genetic_diversity
owl:Class.rdfs:label: genetic diversity
owl:Class.skos:definition: Genetic diversity is the total number of genetic characteristics in the genetic makeup of a species, it ranges widely from the number of species to differences within species and can be attributed to the span of survival for a species. It is distinguished from genetic variability, which describes the tendency of genetic characteristics to vary.

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: from https://encyclopedia2.thefreedictionary.com/geographic+entity
owl:Class.rdfs:label: geographical entity
owl:Class.skos:definition: An entity or geographic feature that occupies a position in space about which data describing the attributes of the entity and its geographic location are recorded.

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: See http://purl.bioontology.org/ontology/CSP/1035-7240
owl:Class.rdfs:label: host organism interaction
owl:Class.skos:definition: interactions between one organism and another which it harbors or nourishes.

owl:Class.rdfs:label: human activity
owl:Class.skos:definition: Actions of human beings that have an influence on the environment and that are characteristic for human societies, i.e. they are linked to social, economic or other cultural processes.

owl:Class.rdfs:label: invasion
owl:Class.skos:definition: The process of transportation, establishment and spread of organisms outside of their native range.

owl:Class.rdfs:label: invasion establishment phase
owl:Class.skos:definition: phase of establishment in the alien range as part of the invasion process

owl:Class.rdfs:label: invasion phase
owl:Class.skos:definition: Sequential phases during the invasion process. Typically, four different phases are distinguished: transport, introduction, establishment and spread.

owl:Class.rdfs:label: invasion spread phase
owl:Class.skos:definition: phase of spreading in the alien range as part of the invasion process

owl:Class.rdfs:label: invasion success
owl:Class.skos:definition: Completing one or all phases of the invasion process.

owl:Class.rdfs:label: invasion transport phase
owl:Class.skos:definition: phase of transportation to the alien range as part of the invasion process

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Alien species that become established and spread beyond the place of introduction are called invasive species.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: invasive species
owl:Class.skos:definition: Alien species that sustain self-replacing populations over several life cycles, produce reproductive offspring, often in very large numbers at considerable distance from the parent and/or site of introduction, and have the potential to spread over long distances.

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: See http://purl.bioontology.org/ontology/MESH/D008027
owl:Class.rdfs:label: light
owl:Class.skos:definition: That portion of the electromagnetic spectrum in the visible, ultraviolet, and infrared range.

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: See http://purl.bioontology.org/ontology/MESH/D018977
owl:Class.rdfs:label: micronutrient
owl:Class.skos:definition: Essential dietary elements or organic compounds that are required in only small quantities for normal physiologic processes to occur.

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Adapted from https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mineral_%28nutrient%29
owl:Class.rdfs:label: mineral nutrient
owl:Class.skos:definition: Chemical element required by organisms to perform functions necessary for life.

owl:Class.rdfs:label: morphological change
owl:Class.skos:definition: Any change in the morpholoy of a species

owl:Class.rdfs:label: morphological phenotype
owl:Class.skos:definition: The form and structure of an organism and its parts, including cells, that result from the interaction of its genotype and the environment. From Bio-Assay Ontology.

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: The rate in which new borns are added to a population, or in other words, the number of new borns over time.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: birth rate
native range
owl:Class.skos:definition: A range in which a species has evolved or in which it has arrived by natural means.

owl:Class.rdfs:label: native species
owl:Class.skos:definition: Species that have evolved in a given area or that arrived there by natural means, without the intentional or accidental intervention of humans from an area where they are native.

owl:Class.rdfs:label: natural disturbance
owl:Class.skos:definition: disturbance that happened by some event not directly caused by human activity, e.g. storms or land slides

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Alien species which are not in the subgroup of invasive species are part of the subgroup non-invasive species.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: non-invasive species
owl:Class.skos:definition: Alien species that is not an invasive species.

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: See http://purl.bioontology.org/ontology/MESH/D000078622
owl:Class.rdfs:label: nutrient
owl:Class.skos:definition: Various components of food that are required for nourishment.

owl:Class.rdfs:label: nutrient content
owl:Class.skos:definition: Amount of nutrients contained in something, e.g in a defined volume of soil or water

owl:Class.rdfs:label: nutrient salt
owl:Class.skos:definition: Nutrient occurring in the chemical form of salt

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: See http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/OBI_0100026
owl:Class.rdfs:label: organism
owl:Class.skos:definition: A material entity that is an individual living system, such as animal, plant, bacteria or virus, that is capable of replicating or reproducing, growth and maintenance in the right environment. An organism may be unicellular or made up, like humans, of many billions of cells divided into specialized tissues and organs.

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: from https://www.thefreedictionary.com/parasite
owl:Class.rdfs:label: parasite
owl:Class.skos:definition: An organism that lives and feeds on or in an organism of a different species and causes harm to its host.

owl:Class.rdfs:label: phenological change
owl:Class.skos:definition: Any change in the phenology of a species

owl:Class.rdfs:label: phenotypic plasticity
owl:Class.skos:definition: The capacity of a genotype to produce different phenotypes in different environments.

owl:Class.rdfs:label: physiological change
owl:Class.skos:definition: Any change in the physioloy of a species

owl:Class.rdfs:label: plant diversity
owl:Class.skos:definition: Variety of plant species present in a location

owl:Class.rdfs:label: plant nutrient
owl:Class.skos:definition: chemical element required by plants to perform functions necessary for life

owl:Class.rdfs:label: population survival
owl:Class.skos:definition: The process of remaining alive or in existence.

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: from https://www.thefreedictionary.com/predator
owl:Class.rdfs:label: predator
owl:Class.skos:definition: An organism that lives by preying on other organisms.

owl:Class.rdfs:label: presence
owl:Class.skos:definition: Being or existing in a specified place or at the specified time.

owl:Class.rdfs:label: primary nutrient
owl:Class.skos:definition: chemical elements required by organisms in large amounts; for plants, these are nitrogen, phosphorus, and potassium

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: See NCIt:C29862
See SNOMEDCT:415178003
See http://www.ifomis.org/bfo/1.1/span#ProcessualEntity
owl:Class.rdfs:label: process
owl:Class.skos:definition: A process is an entity that exists in time by occurring or happening, has temporal parts and always involves and depends on some entity during the time it occurs.
An occurrent [span:Occurrent] that exists in time by occurring or happening, has temporal parts and always involves and depends on some entity.

owl:Class.rdfs:label: propagule pressure
owl:Class.skos:definition: A composite measure consisting of the number of individuals introduced per introduction event and the frequency of introduction events.

owl:Class.rdfs:label: range
owl:Class.skos:definition: An area where a species is found in the wild.

owl:Class.rdfs:label: resistance
owl:Class.skos:definition: staying essentially unchanged despite the presence of disturbances

owl:Class.rdfs:label: resource
owl:Class.skos:definition: Abiotic environmental factor necessary for survival, growth, and reproduction, such as water, light, mineral nutrients, and various forms of fixed carbon (e.g. plant material or meat).

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: See http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/NCIT_C48835
owl:Class.rdfs:label: role
owl:Class.skos:definition: The usual or expected function of something; the part something plays in an action or event.

owl:Class.rdfs:label: secondary nutrient
owl:Class.skos:definition: chemical elements required by organisms in moderate amounts; for plants, these are e.g. sulfur, calcium and magnesium

owl:Class.rdfs:label: specialist
owl:Class.skos:definition: A species that can survive and reproduce only within a narrow range of environmental conditions using specific resources (e.g., a specific diet).

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: from https://doi.org/10.1016/j.tree.2006.02.002
owl:Class.rdfs:label: species trait
owl:Class.skos:definition: A well-defined, measurable property of organisms, usually measured at the individual level and used comparatively across species.

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: from https://www.thefreedictionary.com/subcontinent
owl:Class.rdfs:label: subcontinent
owl:Class.skos:definition: A large landmass, such as India, that is part of a continent but is considered either geographically or politically as an independent entity.

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: See http://purl.bioontology.org/ontology/CSP/1035-7338
owl:Class.rdfs:label: symbiosis
owl:Class.skos:definition: state of close, permanent, or obligatory contact between 2 species, usually of a mutually beneficial nature.

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: See http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/RO_0002577
owl:Class.rdfs:label: system
owl:Class.skos:definition: A material entity consisting of multiple components that are causally integrated.

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: See http://purl.bioontology.org/ontology/MESH/D014131
owl:Class.rdfs:label: trace element
owl:Class.skos:definition: A group of chemical elements that are needed in minute quantities for the proper growth, development, and physiology of an organism. (From McGraw-Hill Dictionary of Scientific and Technical Terms, 4th ed)

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: from http://ncicb.nci.nih.gov/xml/owl/EVS/Thesaurus.owl#C25447
owl:Class.rdfs:label: trait
owl:Class.skos:definition: The distinguishing qualities or prominent aspect of a person, object, action, process, or substance.

owl:Class.rdfs:label: undisturbed ecosystem
owl:Class.skos:definition: An ecosystem that has not been subject to disturbance.
